{{Infobox CanadianMP | honorific-prefix = | name = Serge Cormier | honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}} | image = | imagesize = 200px | office = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Minister of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship]] | minister = [[Ahmed Hussen]] | term_start = January 30, 2017 | term_end = | predecessor = [[Arif Virani]] | successor = | riding1 = [[Acadie-Bathurst]] | parliament1 = Canadian | term_start1 =October 19, 2015 | term_end1 = | predecessor1 = [[Yvon Godin]] | successor1 = | birth_date =1975 | birth_place =[[Maisonnette, New Brunswick]] | death_date = | death_place = | profession = Political assistant | party = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] | residence = | footnotes = | spouse = Annick Pelletier |}}
'''Serge Cormier''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born 1975) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] politician, who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Acadie—Bathurst]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 federal election]].<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/canada-votes-2015-new-brunswick-results-1.3278750</ref>
Cormier's father was an inshore fisherman. He studied business administration, financing his studies by acquiring a small company. He later worked for the government of [[New Brunswick]] as the chief of staff to various government departments, and then as a policy analyst for [[Brian Gallant]] in both the office of the [[Leader of the Opposition (New Brunswick)|Official Opposition]] and of the [[Premier of New Brunswick]]. He served as an advisor to Gallant with responsibility for northern New Brunswick. He worked as a riding organizer for both the federal and provincial Liberal parties.<ref>[https://sergecormier.liberal.ca/biography/ Meet Serge], Liberal.ca.</ref>
On April 27, 2015, he was nominated to be the federal Liberal candidate in [[Acadie—Bathurst]] for the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 election]]. The riding had been held by [[Yvon Godin]] of the [[New Democratic Party]] since 1997, but Godin opted to retire rather than seek re-election, and Cormier ran against [[Jason Godin]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/acadie-bathurst-liberals-nominate-serge-cormier-to-run-in-next-election-1.3049923 Acadie—Bathurst Liberals nominate Serge Cormier to run in next election], CBC News, April 27, 2015.</ref> He won the election, in what was considered an upset victory, as the Liberals swept the Atlantic provinces.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/acadie-bathurst-riding-results-1.3278809 Acadie-Bathurst tilts to Liberal Serge Cormier], CBC News, October 19, 2015.</ref>
He and his wife Annick have two daughters.<ref>[https://sergecormier.liberal.ca/biography/ Meet Serge], Liberal.ca.</ref>
